# Review Phases

Follow these phases in order.

## Phase 1: Intake and Scope

Identify:

- source of existing test cases
- requirement source
- feature/module
- suite name
- suite ID, if available
- project code, if available
- environment or app URL, if available
- repository files inspected
- assumptions and missing inputs

Do not block the review solely because one input is missing. Continue with available information and call out gaps.

---

## Phase 2: Requirements and Coverage Baseline

Extract or infer:

- acceptance criteria
- business rules
- user roles
- entry points
- workflows
- fields
- validations
- permissions
- statuses
- integrations
- data persistence expectations
- negative scenarios
- edge cases
- non-functional expectations

Assign traceability IDs:

- `AC-001` for acceptance criteria
- `BR-001` for business rules
- `PERM-001` for permissions
- `API-001` for API behavior
- `DB-001` for database behavior
- `NFR-001` for non-functional requirements
- `REG-001` for regression risks
- `GAP-001` for missing coverage

---

## Phase 3: Existing Test Case Field Review

Review every test case field by field.

For each field:

- if empty, fill it
- if populated, verify correctness
- if incorrect, update it
- if correct, leave it unchanged and mark no change
- if impossible to determine, flag it as `Needs clarification`

Review these fields:

- Suite
- Title
- Description
- Preconditions
- Steps
- Step action
- Step expected result
- Step test data
- Priority
- Severity
- Type
- Layer
- Behavior
- Automation
- Status
- Is Flaky
- Traceability
- Tags or labels, if used
- Grammar and spelling
- Requirement coverage

---

# Field Standards

## Suite

Suites should be hierarchical and meaningful.

Recommended hierarchy:

```text
Feature Name
├── Smoke Tests
├── Happy Path
├── Negative Cases
├── Edge Cases
├── Security
├── Permissions
├── Integration
├── API
├── Database Validation
└── Accessibility
```

Fix suite placement when:

- a negative case is under Happy Path
- a security case is mixed with generic tests
- smoke tests include too many low-value scenarios
- related tests are scattered across unrelated suites
- suite names are vague, such as `Misc` or `Other`

---

## Title

Use this format:

```text
Verify [expected outcome] when [condition]
```

Rules:

- maximum 70 characters
- prefer 50 to 65 characters
- start with `Verify`
- include outcome and condition
- be specific but not padded
- avoid unnecessary words such as:
  - successfully
  - correctly
  - properly
  - on the page
  - able to
  - check if
  - test that
- include the feature or screen name only when needed for clarity
- avoid duplicate titles within the same suite

Rewrite titles that are:

- empty
- vague
- too long
- grammatically weak
- not outcome-driven
- not aligned with the steps
- using implementation jargon instead of user-observable behavior

Examples:

| Weak Title | Improved Title |
|-----------|----------------|
| Test login | Verify login succeeds with valid credentials |
| Check error on upload | Verify error shown when unsupported file selected |
| User can reset password | Verify reset email is sent for valid email |
| Verify user is able to successfully save the form | Verify form saves when required fields are valid |
| Invalid email test | Verify email validation appears for invalid format |

---

## Description

Description explains what the test validates and why it matters.

Rules:

- 2 to 3 sentences maximum
- do not repeat the title word for word
- do not include credentials
- do not include specific test data
- do not include setup state
- do not include step-by-step instructions
- explain user or business impact

Structure:

```text
This test verifies [behavior being tested]. It matters because [risk or business reason].
```

Bad:

```text
Test login.
Use john@company.com and password Test@123.
```

Good:

```text
This test verifies that an authenticated user can access the dashboard after entering valid credentials. It covers the primary entry point for secured application features.
```

---

## Type

Allowed value:

```text
Regression
```

Qase API value:

```text
type: 3
```

Rules:

- if empty, set to Regression
- if set to anything else, update to Regression

---

## Layer

Allowed value:

```text
E2E
```

Qase API value:

```text
layer: 1
```

Rules:

- if empty, set to E2E
- if set to anything else, update to E2E

---

## Is Flaky

Allowed value:

```text
No
```

Qase API value:

```text
is_flaky: 0
```

Rules:

- manual regression cases should not be marked flaky
- if the case is truly unstable, flag it in review notes instead of marking the formal test as flaky without team agreement

---

## Automation

Allowed value:

```text
Manual
```

Qase API value:

```text
automation: 1
```

Rules:

- set to Manual for these reviewed manual cases
- add automation recommendation separately when the scenario is stable and high-value

---

## Status

Allowed value:

```text
Actual
```

Qase API value:

```text
status: 0
```

Rules:

- if empty, set to Actual
- if obsolete, deprecated, or draft, decide whether to update, archive, or flag for team review

---

## Behavior

Allowed values:

- Positive
- Negative

Qase API values:

```text
Positive: 2
Negative: 3
```

Classify using these signals:

| Signal | Behavior |
|--------|----------|
| valid data | Positive |
| happy path | Positive |
| successful save/update/delete | Positive |
| expected navigation or output | Positive |
| invalid data | Negative |
| missing required field | Negative |
| unsupported file | Negative |
| error message | Negative |
| rejection | Negative |
| permission denial | Negative |
| duplicate prevention | Negative |
| boundary violation | Negative |

Fix behavior when:

- a test marked Positive verifies an error state
- a test marked Negative verifies a valid happy path
- behavior is empty
- title and steps contradict the behavior

---

## Preconditions

Preconditions describe setup state, not test data.

A good precondition includes:

- user role or permission
- required system state
- required existing records
- starting page or navigation point
- feature flag state, if relevant
- environment condition, if relevant

Rules:

- write as a specific paragraph
- no real email addresses
- no real passwords
- no personal names
- no phone numbers
- no exact data values that belong in steps
- no dependency on previous test execution
- each case must be independent and resettable
- avoid vague text such as `User is logged in`

Examples:

Bad:

```text
User is logged in as john@company.com with password Test@123.
```

Good:

```text
User is registered and logged in with Admin-level access. A valid customer record exists. Navigate to the Customer Details page before starting the test.
```

---

## Steps

Each step must have:

- Action
- Expected Result
- Test Data

Use an empty test data value only when the step genuinely requires no input.

### Action Rules

Actions must be:

- atomic
- imperative
- in execution order
- one user action per step
- using exact UI labels where possible
- free from bundled setup
- specific enough for a junior QA to execute

Good action verbs:

- Navigate
- Click
- Enter
- Select
- Clear
- Upload
- Submit
- Confirm
- Cancel
- Refresh
- Observe

Avoid:

- Fill out the form
- Check the page
- Do the login
- Validate everything
- User should be able to

### Expected Result Rules

Expected results must be:

- observable
- present tense
- tied to the action
- specific
- verifiable in UI, API, DB, email, file, or log
- not a repeat of the action

Bad:

```text
Success.
The user clicks Save.
It works.
```

Good:

```text
The Save button becomes enabled.
An inline validation error appears below the Email field.
The user is redirected to the Dashboard page.
The created record appears in the Customer List.
```

### Test Data Rules

Test data is required when the step involves:

- entering text
- entering number or amount
- entering date
- selecting dropdown option
- selecting checkbox/radio value
- uploading file
- sending API payload
- choosing a status
- searching or filtering

Safe placeholders:

| Data Type | Positive | Negative |
|----------|----------|----------|
| Email | `valid-email@test.com` | `invalid-email`, `@missing.com` |
| Password | `ValidPass@123` | `short`, `12345678`, empty |
| Name | `John Doe` | `123`, empty |
| Phone | `+61400000000` | `abc`, `000` |
| Number | `100` | `-1`, `0`, `999999999` |
| Date | `2026-01-15` | `99/99/9999`, invalid date |
| URL | `https://example.com` | `not-a-url` |
| File | `test-document.pdf` | `test-file.csv`, `image.exe` |
| Free text | `Sample text` | empty, 500-character string |
| Search | `customer name` | `<script>alert(1)</script>` |
| UUID / ID | `valid-record-id` | `invalid-id`, deleted record ID |

Rules:

- replace real-looking emails with placeholders
- replace real names and phone numbers with placeholders
- ensure negative test data truly triggers the intended failure
- keep data consistent within the same test case
- use unique suffixes when duplicate records may conflict
- never use production data

---

## Severity and Priority

Severity means impact if the behavior fails in production.

Priority means how urgently the test should be executed.

Review and correct both together.

### Severity Labels

Use these labels in human-readable output:

- Critical
- High
- Medium
- Low

Map to Qase severity values only when calling Qase:

```text
Critical -> 2
High     -> 3
Medium   -> 4
Low      -> 5
```

### Priority Labels

Use these labels in human-readable output:

- High
- Medium
- Low

Map to Qase priority values only when calling Qase:

```text
High   -> 1
Medium -> 2
Low    -> 3
```

### Severity x Priority Matrix

| Scenario Type | Severity | Priority |
|--------------|----------|----------|
| Authentication / login / logout | Critical | High |
| Authorization / role restriction | Critical | High |
| Payment or financial transaction | Critical | High |
| Data loss or corruption prevention | Critical | High |
| Core happy path | High | High |
| Create / update / delete core record | High | High |
| Critical business rule validation | High | High |
| Integration success path | High | High |
| Required field validation | Medium | Medium |
| Invalid input validation | Medium | Medium |
| Boundary validation | Medium | Medium |
| File type or file size rejection | Medium | Medium |
| Permission denial display | High | Medium |
| Search, filter, sort, pagination | Medium | Medium |
| Edge case with low likelihood | Low | Medium |
| Accessibility keyboard path | Medium | Medium |
| Cosmetic or content display issue | Low | Low |

Rules:

- Critical severity always means High priority
- High severity on core flow means High priority
- High severity on a negative permission or error case can be Medium priority
- Medium severity normally means Medium priority
- Low severity normally means Low priority
- if either field is empty, set both
- if both exist but contradict the matrix, update both

---

## Grammar and Style

Check every text field.

Fix:

- spelling
- grammar
- inconsistent tense
- passive or vague wording
- filler words
- duplicated steps
- inconsistent capitalization
- UI labels that do not match implementation
- "user should be able to" wording when a stronger observable result is possible

Use product terminology from the repository, UI, requirements, and knowledge base.

---

# Gap Analysis

After reviewing existing test cases, compare coverage against the baseline.

## Requirement Coverage

Every acceptance criterion should have at least one test.

For each AC:

- positive coverage if the expected behavior should happen
- negative coverage if validation or prevention is involved
- edge coverage when boundaries are specified
- permission coverage when roles are specified
- API/DB coverage when persistence or integration is involved

## UI Coverage

Every discovered UI element should have suitable coverage.

Check:

- fields
- required indicators
- buttons
- dropdowns
- checkboxes
- radio buttons
- tabs
- modals
- confirmation dialogs
- tables
- pagination
- search
- filters
- sorting
- upload controls
- empty states
- error states
- success states

## API Coverage

When APIs are involved, check:

- success response
- validation error response
- authorization failure
- missing required fields
- wrong data type
- invalid enum
- duplicate request
- not found
- conflict
- timeout or server error behavior

## Database Coverage

When data is persisted, check:

- record creation
- record update
- soft delete or hard delete behavior
- audit fields
- status history
- foreign key behavior
- uniqueness
- rollback
- visibility in list/search/detail screens

## Regression Coverage

Check for:

- shared components affected
- downstream modules
- linked screens
- reports/exports
- dashboards
- notifications
- permissions
- existing fixed defects
- integration dependencies

---

# Missing Test Case Creation Rules

When missing scenarios are found, either create the test cases through Qase MCP or provide Qase-ready cases.

Create or recommend cases for:

- missing smoke path
- missing happy path
- missing required-field validation
- missing invalid-format validation
- missing boundary test
- missing permission denial
- missing duplicate prevention
- missing state transition
- missing API failure handling
- missing DB persistence verification
- missing pagination/search/filter scenario
- missing regression scenario from linked module
- missing fixed-defect regression

New cases must follow all field standards in this rule.

---

# Qase Update Rules

When Qase MCP is available, update each changed case using one update call per case.

Do not make separate calls per field.

Update payload must include all corrected fields.

Required Qase values:

```text
type: 3
layer: 1
is_flaky: 0
automation: 1
status: 0
behavior: 2 or 3
severity: per matrix
priority: per matrix
```

Every step object must include:

```text
action
expected_result
data
```

Use empty string for data only when no input is required.

Do not expose enum numbers in the user-facing summary. Use labels instead.

---

# Review Decision Algorithm

For each test case:

1. Read the title, description, preconditions, steps, severity, priority, type, layer, behavior, status, automation, and flaky fields.
2. Identify the tested requirement or mark it as untraced.
3. Verify the test's behavior classification.
4. Verify severity and priority using the matrix.
5. Verify type, layer, status, automation, and flaky values.
6. Verify the description explains purpose and value.
7. Verify preconditions are role/state/start-point based and contain no real data.
8. Verify every step has an atomic action, observable expected result, and appropriate test data.
9. Verify test data is safe, concrete, and aligned with positive or negative behavior.
10. Verify grammar, UI labels, and terminology.
11. Decide:
    - no change
    - update existing case
    - split into multiple cases
    - merge duplicate case
    - mark obsolete
    - create missing case
12. Record the reason for every material change.

---

