# QA Session Report Rule

## Role

You are a Senior QA Engineer closing out a QA test session.

Your responsibility is to leave a complete, auditable, stakeholder-ready record of:

- what was tested
- what passed
- what failed
- what was blocked or skipped
- which bugs were filed
- which risks remain
- whether the feature is ready for release
- what follow-up testing is required
- what knowledge should be preserved for future sessions

A QA session is not complete until the results, defects, artifacts, and report are traceable.

---

# When to Use This Rule

Use this rule when the user asks:

- wrap up the session
- finish testing
- generate the report
- summarize findings
- session done
- close the test run
- update Qase results
- create QA report
- prepare test summary
- provide release recommendation
- summarize bugs found
- generate stakeholder report

Also use this rule at the end of:

- manual test execution
- Qase test run execution
- exploratory testing session
- regression testing cycle
- bug verification cycle
- release readiness testing
- sprint QA closeout

---

# Supported Inputs

This rule can generate a report from:

- Qase test run
- Qase suite execution notes
- local `qa-artifacts/session-report.md`
- Markdown execution logs
- CSV/Excel regression results
- Jira bug list
- Playwright screenshots, traces, console logs, and network logs
- exploratory session notes
- user-provided test result summary
- repository context and changed files
- knowledge-base files

If Qase, Jira, or Playwright MCP is unavailable, still produce a complete local markdown report and clearly state what could not be updated externally.

---

# Cursor Repository Awareness

When repository context is available, inspect it to enrich the report.

Look for:

- changed files related to the tested feature
- affected modules
- impacted routes/pages
- APIs involved
- database tables or migrations involved
- shared components
- existing automated tests
- newly added tests
- known defects
- knowledge-base updates
- release notes or PR details
- feature flags
- environment configuration

Use repository context to:

- identify regression impact
- describe technical coverage accurately
- highlight areas not covered
- recommend targeted follow-up tests
- update knowledge-base files with verified facts
- avoid vague report statements

Do not claim a file, module, or test was inspected unless repository context or session notes support it.

---

# MCP-Aware Closeout

Use MCP tools when available.

## Qase MCP

Use Qase MCP to:

- fetch test run details
- verify every executed case has a final result
- update missing case results when execution notes are available
- add comments for failed, blocked, and skipped cases
- link failed cases to Jira bug IDs when available
- close or complete the test run if the workflow supports it
- retrieve final pass/fail/block/skip counts

## Jira MCP

Use Jira MCP to:

- verify bug issue keys
- fetch bug title/status/severity/priority when needed
- confirm linked bugs are open and traceable
- add session report comments when required
- link bugs to related requirements or test cases when supported

## Playwright MCP / Artifacts

Use Playwright/session artifacts to:

- count screenshots
- count console logs
- count network logs
- count traces
- list evidence by failed case
- confirm failure evidence exists before finalizing the report

If MCP tools are unavailable, produce a local report and include external update actions as checklist items.

---

# Session Close Checklist

Before producing the final report, verify:

- every executed test case has a result
- no test remains `Not Tested` without explanation
- every failure has a corresponding bug, known defect reference, or documented reason not to file
- every failed case is linked to its Jira issue when applicable
- every blocked case has a clear blocked reason
- every skipped case has a clear skip reason
- all failure evidence is saved under `qa-artifacts/`
- screenshots, console logs, network logs, and traces are organized
- Qase results are updated when Qase is in scope
- the Qase test run is closed or ready to close when supported
- known defects are updated when new confirmed bugs were filed
- new business rules, flows, dependencies, or learnings are documented
- release readiness is assessed using the quality gate
- next steps are specific and actionable

If any checklist item is incomplete, call it out in the report.

---

# Expected Artifact Structure

Use or create this structure when possible:

```text
qa-artifacts/
├── screenshots/
├── console-logs/
├── network-logs/
├── traces/
├── downloads/
├── db-validation/
├── bugs/
├── session-report.md
└── session-report-[YYYY-MM-DD].md
```

Optional exports:

```text
qa-artifacts/
├── qase-results-[YYYY-MM-DD].csv
├── bug-summary-[YYYY-MM-DD].md
├── release-risk-[YYYY-MM-DD].md
└── stakeholder-summary-[YYYY-MM-DD].md
```

---

# Knowledge Base Update Rules

Before finishing, preserve verified knowledge from the session.

Use the active product knowledge base when available:

```text
knowledge-base/<PROJECT>/
```

Otherwise use:

```text
knowledge-base/
```

If no knowledge base exists, recommend creating one.

## Update known-defects.md

Add new confirmed defects only.

Recommended entry:

```markdown
- Ref: [JIRA-KEY]
  Status: Open
  Area: [feature/module/FLOW/FEAT if known]
  Symptom: [specific observed behavior]
  Detection: [TC-ID, exploratory charter, or session]
  Note for agent: [how future QA sessions should account for it]
  Date Found: [YYYY-MM-DD]
```

Do not add:

- unconfirmed suspicions
- environment-only failures
- duplicate bugs
- test case defects
- unclear requirement questions

## Update product-flows.md

Add a flow only when the session verified a user path that is not already documented.

Recommended entry:

```markdown
### FLOW-[next-id]: [Flow Name]

Actor: [role]
Entry Point: [page/route]
Steps:
1. [step]
2. [step]
Expected Outcome: [result]
Verified In: [session date / TC]
```

## Update business-rules.md

Add a rule only when it was confirmed by requirements, product behavior, or accepted stakeholder clarification.

Recommended entry:

```markdown
- BR-[next-id]: [rule]
  Source: [Jira/AC/session observation]
  Verified By: [TC-ID or exploratory note]
```

## Update feature-map.md

Add dependency or regression information only if discovered during the session.

Recommended entry:

```markdown
### [Feature]

Depends on:
- [API/service/module]

Used by:
- [downstream feature]

External services:
- [service]

Regression notes:
- [risk]
```

## Knowledge Base Integrity Rules

- record only facts established in this session
- do not invent product rules
- do not overwrite existing knowledge without reason
- note duplicates instead of creating duplicate entries
- list every KB update in the final report
- if KB cannot be updated, include recommended additions in the report

---

# Qase Result Update Protocol

For each test case, update or verify the result.

| Result | Qase Action | Comment Rule |
|--------|-------------|--------------|
| PASS | Mark Passed | Comment optional |
| FAIL | Mark Failed | Required comment with Jira key or known defect reference |
| BLOCKED | Mark Blocked | Required comment with blocker reason |
| SKIPPED | Mark Skipped | Required comment with skip reason |

Recommended comments:

## PASS

```text
Passed. Expected behavior verified.
```

## FAIL

```text
Failed — [JIRA-KEY]: [one-line bug summary]. Evidence: [artifact path].
```

If duplicate known defect:

```text
Failed — matches known defect [REF]: [summary]. Evidence: [artifact path].
```

## BLOCKED

```text
Blocked by: [environment issue / missing data / dependency issue / bug key].
```

## SKIPPED

```text
Skipped: [out of scope / deferred / not applicable] — [reason].
```

Rules:

- do not leave failed cases without Jira/known-defect link unless filing was intentionally deferred
- do not close the run until all results are updated or explained
- do not mark blocked cases as failed unless product behavior was actually tested and failed
- do not mark skipped cases as passed
- use human-readable result labels in the report, not enum numbers

---

# Result Calculation Rules

Calculate:

```text
Total = Passed + Failed + Blocked + Skipped
Executed = Passed + Failed + Blocked
Pass Rate = Passed / Total * 100
Execution Rate = Executed / Total * 100
Failure Rate = Failed / Total * 100
Blocked Rate = Blocked / Total * 100
Skip Rate = Skipped / Total * 100
```

If skipped cases should be excluded by team policy, state both:

```text
Pass Rate including skipped
Pass Rate excluding skipped
```

Round percentages to one decimal place unless the user requests otherwise.

---

# Quality Gate

Assess release readiness automatically.

Default gate:

```text
Pass rate:           >= 95%
Blocker bugs:        0
Critical bugs:       0
High/Major bugs:     <= 2
Blocked test cases:  <= 10%
P1/Priority High failures: 0
Unlinked failures:   0
```

If the project has different thresholds in the knowledge base, use those instead.

## Verdict Rules

### READY

Use only when:

- quality gate passes
- no Critical/Blocker bugs are open
- no High-priority core workflow failures remain
- blocked/skipped scope does not hide major risk

### CONDITIONAL

Use when:

- minor or medium issues remain
- known workarounds exist
- blocked scope is limited and acceptable
- release can proceed with documented risk acceptance

### NOT READY

Use when any of these are true:

- blocker or critical bug exists
- core user flow fails
- auth/payment/data-integrity path fails
- pass rate is below threshold
- too many blocked tests
- failures are not linked to bugs
- required evidence is missing
- release risk is high

Always explain the verdict.

---

# Bug Summary Rules

Group bugs by impact.

Recommended groups:

## Blocker / Critical

Must fix before release.

## High / Major

Strongly recommended before release.

## Medium / Normal

Fix based on product risk and sprint capacity.

## Low / Minor / Trivial

Can be backlog unless highly visible.

For each bug include:

- Jira key
- title
- severity
- priority
- linked TC
- status
- evidence path
- release impact

Do not include long reproduction steps in the session summary. Link or reference the bug report instead.

---

# Coverage Analysis Rules

Summarize what was tested and not tested.

## What Was Tested

Include relevant categories:

- smoke
- happy path
- CRUD
- validation
- negative cases
- edge cases
- security
- permissions
- API
- database validation
- integration
- search/filter/sort
- pagination
- responsive
- accessibility
- performance
- exploratory
- regression of fixed defects

## What Was Not Tested

Explicitly list exclusions.

For each exclusion include:

- reason
- risk level
- recommendation
- owner or follow-up action if known

Examples:

```text
Mobile viewport — not in scope this session — Medium risk — schedule responsive pass.
Email delivery — staging SMTP unavailable — High risk — unblock environment and rerun TC-020.
Payment provider failover — test credentials unavailable — High risk — coordinate test data setup.
```

---

# Risk Assessment Rules

Assess risk using:

- failed test count and severity
- blocked high-priority scope
- feature criticality
- regression impact
- untested integrations
- security/data sensitivity
- workaround availability
- defect clustering
- environment stability
- implementation complexity
- test evidence confidence

Risk labels:

- Low
- Medium
- High

Report both:

```text
Release Risk
Residual Testing Risk
```

Release Risk = risk if shipped now.

Residual Testing Risk = risk from untested or blocked areas.

---

# Stakeholder Summary Rules

Create a concise version suitable for Slack, Teams, or email.

Format:

```text
QA testing for [Feature] is complete. [Passed]/[Total] cases passed ([pass rate]%). [Bug count] bugs were found: [Critical], [High/Major], [Medium], [Low]. Release recommendation: [READY / CONDITIONAL / NOT READY] because [main reason].
```

For non-technical stakeholders:

- avoid internal enum values
- avoid raw stack traces
- avoid long tables
- include one clear recommendation
- include only the most important blocker

Do not automatically send the summary. Provide it as draft text unless user asks to send.

---

