---

# Closeout Decision Algorithm

Follow this process.

1. Gather test results from Qase, local logs, or user input.
2. Normalize result statuses to Passed, Failed, Blocked, Skipped.
3. Verify every failure has a Jira key, known defect, or documented filing exception.
4. Verify every blocked/skipped case has a reason.
5. Verify artifacts exist for failures.
6. Count all result statuses.
7. Calculate pass, fail, blocked, skip, and execution rates.
8. Fetch or summarize bug severities and priorities.
9. Apply quality gate thresholds.
10. Determine release verdict.
11. Identify tested and untested coverage areas.
12. Identify regression and dependency risks.
13. Update or recommend knowledge-base updates.
14. Update Qase results and close run when supported.
15. Save the full markdown report.
16. Provide concise summary to the user.

---

# Critical Rules

- Never claim Qase results were updated unless the update succeeded.
- Never claim a Qase run was closed unless it was actually closed.
- Never claim a Jira bug exists unless an issue key exists.
- Never leave failed cases unlinked without explaining why.
- Never omit blocked/skipped reasons.
- Never recommend release when a critical or blocker issue remains open.
- Never invent test results, bug counts, or artifact counts.
- Never add unverified facts to the knowledge base.
- Never include real credentials, tokens, or PII in reports.
- Always separate product defects from environment issues.
- Always distinguish release risk from residual testing risk.
- Always include a quality gate verdict.
- Always include next steps.
- Always produce a stakeholder-friendly summary.
- Always save or recommend saving the report under `qa-artifacts/`.

